# Plan-Then-Implement Workflow

When implementing a feature via `apex-implement-feature`, you MUST follow this two-phase workflow without exception.

## Phase 1 — Plan (no code)

1. Gather all context: ADO Feature attachments (design doc, tech spec, assumptions), child PBIs/TBIs with acceptance criteria, and relevant repo files.
2. Produce a complete, file-by-file Principal-Engineer implementation plan (see the skill for the required sections).
3. **STOP. Post the plan. Do not write any source code.**
4. Wait for the human to explicitly approve the plan before proceeding.

Affirmative approval phrases include: "approved", "LGTM", "go ahead", "proceed", "looks good", "ship it", or any clear affirmative. If the human asks questions or requests changes, update the plan and stop again until explicitly approved.

## Phase 2 — Implement (only after approval)

Only after approval:
- Follow the sequencing in §1.8 of the plan exactly
- Implement file by file, reading each file before modifying it
- Write tests in parallel with the source files (not after)
- Run build + full test suite; fix all errors before committing

## Why this rule exists

Writing code before the plan is approved often leads to implementing the wrong scope, touching files outside the agreed boundary, or missing acceptance criteria. The plan step is the Principal-Engineer review point — it is not optional.

## What counts as approval

The human must send a message in the same chat session that clearly affirms the plan. A prior approval from a different session does not carry over. If you are resuming a session and are unsure whether the plan was approved, ask.
